<Rate>3<//Rate>< text>
This place has been on my radar for quite a while but I never pulled the trigger because I‚Äôm pretty loyal to my usual favorite wing spot in town. But one day I had some time free after a photoshoot so I decided to give it a shot. I ordered a ten-piece lemon pepper because let‚Äôs be honest‚Ä¶ lemon pepper is the only flavor that matters. The wings were A-MAZING!! Hot, fresh, a good size, perfectly fried with the perfect amount of lemon-pepper. Could this be my new favorite wing spot? Well not so fast‚Ä¶ I like to give a new place at least three chance before I proclaim anything because anyone can have a good day and anyone can have a bad day, hits and misses happen everywhere.

The second time I went there I got a twenty-piece. Now‚Ä¶ the wings were good BUT they didn‚Äôt have that same magic as the first time and they were also a little undercooked. Not by a lot, but a self proclaimed wing connoisseur like myself can tell. See what I mean about the ‚Äúhit and miss?‚Äù So I went back a third time and this time I got a meal. I believe it was the five piece with the fries and drink. Now here‚Äôs where this place rubbed me the wrong way. Each of the two other times I was helped by a younger women and I was just charged my meal. This time it was an older woman and she told me that if I wanted to use my credit card I would be charged .50. I work for an indie mom & pop store in town so I understand WHY the CC charge, but either they charged me that free the first two times and didn‚Äôt say anything‚Ä¶ OR they pick and choose which customers they charge the .50 fee. And I didn‚Äôt see that posted anywhere (yeah, I looked)

This is the type of inconsistency with businesses that drive me crazy. Admittedly I‚Äôm hyper-sensitive about this because of‚Ä¶ certain reasons. But if you‚Äôre going to charge a CC fee then 1. Make it public and 2. Make sure all your employees do this. Otherwise it seems random and unfair. Three visits all within ten days. And even though I LOVE their wings, I haven‚Äôt been back because of this. If I do go back I‚Äôll bring cash just so I don‚Äôt have to bring this up and cause an awkward situation.<//text>

< Review>
I had milk tea boba and it was terrible. Boba had a bad texture and the tea was not great either. I am spoiled in LA with world class boba shops, but just wanted to let the world know that this wasn't one of them. Also, the price was 4.01. I couldn't use my credit card without a 50 cent fee and there was no penny bin. I asked if she could just ignore the penny, but she didn't answer and proceeded to give me 99 cents change. That's the price, so fine, but who sets their price of one of the two items in their freakin Name to be 4.01, and then discourages use of credit cards?<//Review>

However, when trying to place an order for pick-up the website indicates the restaurant is only taking phone orders and when I did attempt to call (for over 30 minutes) their line was busy. < Review>
Instagram: @koganei037

1st Impression:
From the outside it looks like it got a lot of space but once you go in, you realize that the space is only long but not far in. Making larger groups hard to be seated.
Other than that, the bar area and overall ambiance is nice and clean.

Food Impression:
The Pan Roast here is ok but I've had better in other places.
This one still cannot compare to the Oyster Bar located inside Palace Station in Las Vegas.
The heat numbering is a joke. I ordered a 7 while a friend of mine ordered a 8 (1 to 10), we both barely got any heat on our Pan Roasts and Gumbo.

Price Impression:
The price is about the same with other places that serves the same type of food but because of the lack of quality, it's just ok.

Conclusion:
Better save your money and try somewhere else than here. The cost is not worth trying an ok place for Pan Roast.<//Review>

102918253898437847981< /userid>
<gmapID>0x80dd2143cf92ab6b:0xd7bc543c8625f45a</gmapID><time>1526354306354< /time><Review>Ritter me this, Batman!

What do you get when you cross an owl with a bungee cord??

............................My ass!! BWAHAHAHAHAHAHAHA

Free appetizer with any entr√©e purchase coupon

Ritter's Steam Kettle Cooking serves up authentic Creole cuisine, utilizing individual jacketed steam kettles to evenly cook food at varying temperatures.  I've had this place on my radar for awhile now, and lunch seemed the perfect opportunity to stop by.

While the restaurant seems small, the table & bar seating can accommodate around 30 people.  Flatscreen TV's had international soccer & soap operas for my viewing pleasure.

A complimentary crusty bread roll w/ butter greeted me as I gave the menu a once over.

For my free appetizer, I went with the deep fried bacon wrapped molasses marinated shrimp & mozzarella with molasses mustard-
Bacon & shrimp, two of my favorite food groups.  Large, tender shrimp wrapped in smoky, fatty bacon, with a delicious mustard for dipping.  If that's not enough, gooey mozzarella cheese just for the hell of it.  Some hot sauce kicked up the molasses mustard to my liking.

For my entr√©e, I chose the clam pan roast (spice level 7)-
Tomato cream base with Cajun trinity & jasmine rice.  A rainy day comfort food.  Rich, hearty, stick to your ribs kind of dish.  The level 7 spice level was just right for me, providing heat while still allowing me to taste all the bold flavors encompassed in the bowl.  Plenty of sweet clam swimming in the tomato broth, a scoop of fluffy rice wading in the middle.  My only complaint, and it's more a personal preference, is next time I'll ask for rice on the side.  Reason being is that I'm not particularly fond of soggy rice.  As I got down to the last few bites, the soggy rice grains became unappetizing to me.  But, the large portions & tremendous flavor have made me a fan.

Beignet with chocolate whipped cream-
I've only had beignets previously at Ralph Brennan's Jazz Kitchen, and Ritter's seemed more dense & textured.  The chocolate whipped cream was ambrosia to me.  With a liberal slathering on top of the fried dough calorie buster, the flavor was heavenly.  Perfect way to end the meal.

Service was great.  I was attended to promptly & had plenty of soda water w/lime refills.  Parking is metered in the front, with a structure available nearby.  The parking structure is only $2 for the first two hours.

C'est si bon!  Ritter's Steam Kettle Cooking offers delicious Creole cuisine in a relaxing atmosphere.  I'm highly anticipating coming back & trying their other dishes such as jambalaya & chowder.  Besides beignets, Ritter's also offers bread pudding a la mode and that has my undivided attention for my next visit.

Highly recommend!
NOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOMNOM</Review><resp>None<//resp>< username>

One of the more unique food experiences you can get in downtown Huntington Beach. It is sort quaint (small) but one of the few places with counter service where lone diners can eat without taking up a table and stares of other patrons. The service was very attentive and helpful. I had the pan toast and had the chowder before and intend to get the gumbo in the future. Of the 2 I have had, I prefer the chowder, but it appears the pan roast is most everyone else's favorite.</text>

The prawns were a good texture, not overcooked and the heat level was nice and not overpowering. I will say that they red sauce was very basic and left me wanting something more complex but that's not to say it wasn't good just not great. I finished up with some beignets for dessert which were made great, fluffy and crispy on the outside but still slightly doughy and soft on the inside with a pocket of air. It was slow when we came in,  so I can't really speak to overall service.  However,  with that said, my service was excellent.   My order was make incorrectly and it was remedied quickly.  I had the cioppino. I would say it was no more than a 4 out of 5. <userid>111040063389210958990<//userid><name>Dominique Tran<//name><Time>1457349752750< /Time><Rating>4</Rating>< review>
Pretty good place for a southern taste.

The restaurant is a bit small, holding maybe 40 people at most. It's a cozy place though. They have nice decor and have their cooking stream pots lined up along the bar. It actually gets kinda hot sitting at the bar when they cook.

The food was good. We had their oysters and their house pot roast. I felt that the oysters were fresh. The pot roast was good as well. The amount of lobster and shrimp was substantial and it tastes overall very good.

Overall, it is a bit pricey but it may become my goto place for oysters.< /review>

This is the perfect place to get some creole classics served up fresh, fast, and right in front you (if you sit along the counter). This was a really unique experience as I'd never been to a place with steam kettle cooking and they have several of them lined up that they use to prepare their liquid based entrees. Overall, service was good and the food is flavorful! If you love seafood and food that has soul, then this is for you!< /Text>

< Review>
Honestly, if I could give zero stars I would. My husband and I usually go to the Santa Ana location but decided to give this one a try for our anniversary dinner. We were very disappointed. Staff was extremely rude. We were told to sit wherever, and someone came and tossed the menus on the table without saying a word. The host also reached over me twice, once was over my purse (very uncomfortable for me) to get something on the counter in front of me, second was to hand my husband bread but he did so over my plate instead of walking to where my hubby was sitting, not once did anyone say excuse me. The food also tasted horrible, not at all how it should taste, they also got hubby's food order wrong, he ordered the gumbo with everything in it but pretty much only got fish and an odd piece of chicken. We will never return to this location. If you want to eat at Ritter's PLEASE go to the santa ana location!

-Mrs.Hodges</Review>

< name>
Gina Banh</name>
< Date>
1457351090013<//Date>
<rate>4<//rate>< review>
I really enjoyed my whole experience here. Not only was the food delicious but the atmosphere was fun and inviting. We sat in the bar area, which I personally love because it is very close to the steam pots that they use to cook the gumbo and pan roasts. Like the other review says, it does get really hot from all the steam but it smelled great as well. We got oysters and the seafood pan roast. Both were delicious and enough to more than fulfill the appetite of two fatties. They are also presented very aesthetically so get your instagram ready! The price is mediocre, pretty much the same as any other southern cajun restaurant.  ~$20 for the house panroast (highly suggested) and $18 for a dozen oysters.< /review>

<user>107856096311366382076</user><Name>Michael Von der Porten< /Name><date>1420156425002<//date><rating>4<//rating><text>Quite good standard Chinese fare.

We had theHouse Deluxe Won Ton Soup (large $7.55), Coconut Shrimp ($12.25), Moo Shi Pork ($7.95) and Egg Plant in Brown Sauce ($7.75).

Each was quite good.

The brown sauce was better than at most Chinese restaurants.

As expected, there is good value here.

Service was good, but with the take-out and delivery business, they could have used an additional service person that evening.

The only negative here is that the restrooms were clean, but really need a remodel.

We'd come by again when we are in the area.<//text>< pics>

< Review>
I read the reviews and decided to take a chance on the Watch Buyers Group.This was the first time my Rolex GMT Master has ever been serviced by anyone other than Rolex. From the moment I sent the request for shipping documents until the watch was returned today, the experience could not have been better. I received and email when the watch arrived, another email a couple of days later after the watch was examined with a list of items that needed fixed and another list of optional items to restore my watch to new. Once we agreed on what I wanted repaired, the finished the repairs, cleaned and polished the watch and returned to me.

The price was reasonable and I must admit I forgot how the watch was supposed to work. The repairs were performed including replacing a couple of parts with Rolex OEM pieces. My 20 year old daily wearer watch is back in amazing condition. The appraisal was better than I expected.

I was looking to replace my bracelet and the WBG scoured their sources to find me a band. I can't speak, or even shout, highly enough about The Watch Buyers Group.

I've worn my SS Submariner Date 24/7 since I purchased it in November 1987, and its last service was ~ 20 years ago. It was "well used" and had developed a number of issues. TWBG did a FANTASTIC job...it looks new!  Not just to me, but two absolute strangers have asked me "when did you get your Rolex?".  Both were shocked when I said "1987", and commented that they thought it was brand new. That impression continued even after a closer examination.

I made my choices, the work was done promptly, and they worked with me to handle my unusual requirements for shipping - all included in their free return shipping.

Best of all, my Sub works perfectly and is BEAUTIFUL. I couldn't be happier and if it were possible, I'd give them 6 stars.</Text>

<Pics>None< /Pics><date>1582758628747</date>< Review>
5 months ago i would say avoid this place but after meeting Jarrod Mills. I love this place now! 4 months ago i met with Aaron (Manager). I was going to sign up with the $100 enrollment fee and $20 monthly but he kept trying to push the 4 day training sessions on me even after i said no thanks im good like 4x in person (at least 7x over the phone). He asked why, i told him my wife and I are expecting a baby in 5 months....So i do my 7 day free trial, i only go 2 days because Aaron kept calling me during my work days and while i was at the gym still trying to get me to sign up. The last deal he gave me was $60 off the enrollment fee (i still said no). So to make this long story short everyone there is very pushy and are all about their numbers and sales. Now on January 18th my cousin takes me back to meet Jarrod Mills and this guy is easy to talk to not pushy and because of how he treats guests is the reason i signed up. I paid $100 enrollment fee and i also signed up with a trainer for $200 (Jarrod can help you pick a trainer that will work for you but if you need a trainer ask for Dom). Reason he got me to buy and sign up was due to the fact he didn't treat me like a sale. So if you are thinking about signing up and want a great experience ask for Jarrod. He will make you feel comfortable and can relate to anyone from fit to someone who is just getting started.<//Review>

< Name>
Shirley Pena</Name>
< date>
1390085435969<//date>
< rating>
1<//rating>
< text>
HERE are the positive and negative aspects of using the Porterville branch:
POSITIVE
1. The staff are always friendly, courteous and respectful
2. The steam room is CONTINUOUSLY cleaned by the housekeeping staff
3. The sauna is regularly cleaned by the housekeeping staff
4. The trainers are friendly, courteous and work especially well with handicapped patrons
5. There is never a fuss over how many clean towels one requests-use as many as you want
6. The instructors for special classes (yoga, etc.) are friendly, courteous, respectful and work
especially well with patrons who are fifty+

NEGATIVE
1. There is only ONE pool, and it frequently has the heating unit not working properly
2. There is only ONE whirlpool-and it frequently either looks grubby or is closed
for cleaning during PEAK HOURS OF USE, rather than during the wee hours of the
night and morning as one would expect
3. Dirty/wet towels left on the locker room floors and shower stalls are VERY common
4. All but ONE of the shower stalls lack proper, hand-held shower equipment
5. All but ONE of the shower stalls lack a bench to sit on for patrons who cannot stand
6. All but ONE of the shower stalls are so tiny that one cannot move about freely
7. Unlike the other branches, the Porterville branch totally lacks tvs in the locker rooms
8. Unlike the other branches, the Porterville branch totally lacks a leisure room for its patrons
to gather at/socialize

Currently, the most SERIOUS problem with the Porterville branch is that it is undergoing an extensive
(and leisurely!) RE-MODELING to bring it up to the standards of the other branches. Part of that re-modeling has resulted in all of the locker rooms/shower and toilet facilities being CLOSED to its patrons!

Needless to say, this is terribly UNHEALTHY-not to mention highly inconvenient-for all its patrons, but especially more so for those families with small children!! Rather than close the branch while it undergoes this extensive and prolonged period of re-modeling, allowing its contracted patrons a relief from their monthly dues during this period, it has unwisely chosen to remain OPEN, forcing its patrons to have to endure the discomfort of being sweaty/unclean after their workout! This problem is especially alarming for those patrons who continue to use the pool and the whirlpool, since use of either or both naturally constitutes a higher probability of coming into contact with bacteria...and no effective way to wash it off oneself EXCEPT for the use of the cold water hose present near the pool! Imagine how grossly uncomfortable it is trying to hose oneself off during the WINTER!

Even more alarming, with the current lack of toilet facilites, is the high probability that children using the pool are...ahem...using it in a manner it WAS NOT intended for (Kids:"Hey everyone! Let's PEE IN THE POOL!") and I will bet the farm that the ADULTS are doing the same!

Overall, considering all the plus and minus factors at work here, I currently give it ONE STAR because without access to toilets, showers and wash basins for it's patrons, it is basically UNFIT TO USE! Had this NOT been the current situation, I would have given the Porterville branch of In-Shape City a solid three-star rating.</text>

<user_id>100628241609761386745< /user_id><name>Jared Cohee<//name><Date>1557115640312</Date><Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
M√âXICO üá≤üáΩ
Eat the World LA review:
East Olympic Blvd in Boyle Heights might currently be the epicenter of the Los Angeles taco truck power rankings, with all-stars like Tacos y Birria La Unica, Mariscos Jalisco and Los Originales Tacos √Årabes de Puebla. But before Jonathan Gold sent Mariscos Jalisco shooting for the stars, the truck with the longest lines was probably going to be Mariscos 4 Vientos on any given day, and for good reason.

The original truck and bricks and mortar at 3000 E. Olympic Blvd have been going strong for over a decade, with recent expansions further east to the intersection of S. Lorena Street, where two additional locations have offered a similar popular menu.

With the sounds of tractor trailers and the smells of diesel fumes, it is almost a miracle this casual restaurant on the corner can be so comfortable and relaxing. A little later in the day, the spot tucked across the street on Lorena offers beers with your meal. Either way, sometimes you are just in the mood for a table and these locations serve that need better than the lonchera.< /review>

<Review>I live in Victorville California and I drive over 80 miles one way to this hidden gem in Boyle Heights California especially for the fried shirmp tacos $2.50 each,! that I highly recommend! You get half an avacado for every 3 tacos which I usually order 6. The mixed seafood tostada is super delicious but a little pricey @ $9.50. Another fair priced is the octopus shirmp cocktail. Lillie Cast<//Name>
<time>1582929715294<//time><rate>3< /rate>< Text>
I made a phone order to pick up and I still had to stand in line, a very long line, to pay and then they still made me wait for my order. The food was delicious... although I'm told that the restaurant food and the fast food truck that sits out front have different flavors. That is why many want to eat from the truck and not the restaurant. They should have a line for phone orders so that customers can just pay and pick up instead of standing in a long line with everyone else who didn't phone in. I like organization and cleanliness. The truck out side parks in an area that is not so clean. I'm not sure if the food is worth all that. The shrimp tacos are good from the truck but they need better organization.</Text>

< Text>
Delicious tacos. Simple place. Simple menu: fish taco(2.25), shrimp taco (2.25) and lemonade (1.00). Surprisingly delicious. You have a bar of salsas to choose from, cabbage and crema. All assemble yourself. They hand you the tacos ordered.
Only thing I would change would be that the salsas weren't kept cold with ice when I got there. It was all melted.
Ask for limes and enjoy!
Plenty of seating outside.
Employees are pleasant and welcoming :)
Everything is done fresh, you can see them working in the back.< /Text>

< Review>
I'm not a fan of taco dorado's because to me theyre always somewhat dry, but omg... not with this place.  The taco was still nice and crunchy but the strip filling with delicious and moist. The avocado that comes on top adds a silky creamy bite and flavor. And to top it off, the salsa that's on top was delicious. I usually enjoy the more spicy salsas, but this one was more on the mild side and delicious. If you get a chance to go, do it! Just bring cash though, no cards.< /Review>

0x80c2c8b107ba534f:0x26139bf0de9bcfec<//GmapID>
<response>None<//response>< Text>
What are the odds of discovering two of the best shrimp tacos in town just within a block from each other? On the way to trying out Mariscos Jalisco, I stopped by Mariscos 4 Vientos first. I ordered two of their famous shrimp tacos. Much less foot traffic than their neignbor, Jalisco, and order came out instantly!! Just from the look of the tacos they were nothing impressive. When I took my first bite, my whole world changed. I experience that crunchy exterior and that chunky shrimp I can taste from each bite. After few bites, I realized that I was slurping the excess salsa straight from the plate. By far the best shrimp tacos I've ever had. I can say that I enjoyed more so than their next door neighbor Jalisco. I wanted to go for more but then I stopped myself for the next trip.</Text>

<Text>this is a lunch truck that is always in this same location everyday the locals really like this spot you see this is a location that the lunch truck always serves and in the corner building they have tables where you can sit with your family, not a lot of people know about this place but even then this place gets full. theres always a very long line to eat here. their specialty tacos de camaron(shrimp tacos) they served oysters shrimp or/and octopus cocktails the food is delicious but when you order you have to be talk loud so they can hear you don't be shy that's just how it is, you'll really like this place if you like Mexican food. :-)
